</span></span><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
color:black'>high blood pressure, which is most often due to hypertension, but
can also occur as a result of other diseases.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>Diabetes mellitus is
characterized by hyperglycemia (high blood glucose), hyperlipidemia (high lipid
levels), increased pressure in the capillaries of the renal glomeruli and
secondary arterial hypertension, which, on the one hand, is a consequence of
kidney damage, and on the other hand, aggravates renal failure.&nbsp;Hyperglycemia
negatively affects the kidneys: there is a change in the structure of the
proteins of the renal membranes, a direct toxic effect on the kidney tissue,
the release of free radicals, which also have a toxic effect on the cells of
various organs.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
14.0pt;margin-left:0in;line-height:normal'><span lang=EN-US style='font-size:
13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;color:black'>For the correct
functioning of the kidneys, blood pressure must be no higher than 130
mm.&nbsp;rt.&nbsp;Art, otherwise the filtration process is disrupted.&nbsp;Even
a slight increase in blood pressure leads to impaired renal function.&nbsp;If
the filtration process fails, inflammatory mechanisms and factors are triggered
that cause vasoconstriction, which leads to an even greater increase in
pressure in the renal vessels, causes the death of nephrons (a structural unit
of the kidneys), and the remaining nephrons take on an increased load, but
decompensation occurs over time and progressive decline in renal function.</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:14.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-bottom:
